is unavoidable:} Qc8 ({or} 29... dxc4 30. d5) 30. c5 {etc.}) 23. Bxc7 $1 {(5)}
Qxc7 24. Nxd5 Qd6 {(9)} ({This gives better chances of a defence than} 24...
Rxe2 25. Nxc7 Re1+ 26. Kh2 Bd6+ 27. g3 Bxc7 {, since here the coordination of
Black's forces is disrupted and White begins advancing his pawns with} 28. c4
$1 {, virtually forcing the win of a piece.}) 25. Nxe7+ Bxe7 26. Qe4 Bf8 {A
critical moment in the game. Now much depends on what plan White chooses. Alas,
